Synclime System Architecture: Database and IPC Route Blueprint

This document outlines the complete storage schema and backend communication routing layers of Synclime. The backend leverages an embedded SQLite database managed via Rusqlite, and a high-performance IPC (Inter-Process Communication) network built on Tauri v2.
1. Database Engine Architecture Overview

Synclime uses a single relational SQLite database file (synclime_core.db) stored securely inside the operating system's local application data directory.
Why this design was chosen:

    ACID Transactions: Ensures that file queue operations, download states, and error tracking remain perfectly synchronized even during sudden power losses or application crashes.

    Foreign Key Constraints: Structured with ON DELETE CASCADE and ON DELETE SET NULL properties to maintain strict data integrity. For example, if a parsed playlist configuration is deleted, all sub-tasks nested under that playlist are cleanly handled.

    Indexed Performance: Custom indexes are applied to status columns, queue priorities, and timestamps to ensure that UI data fetches take less than 1 millisecond, even with thousands of files in the queue.

2. Table-by-Table Database Schema Design
Table 1: cookie_profiles

    Purpose: Stores localized web browser cookie session data blocks. This allows the backend to authenticate downloads from private accounts or premium subscription platforms.

    Field Breakdown:

        slug (TEXT PRIMARY KEY): A unique, URL-safe text identifier generated for the profile.

        title (TEXT): A user-friendly label (e.g., "My Personal YouTube Premium Account").

        domain (TEXT): The target web domain this profile belongs to (e.g., "youtube.com").

        cookie_data (TEXT): The raw token string or file path mapping authentication details.

        created_at / updated_at (TEXT): ISO-8601 string timestamps for record synchronization.

Table 2: proxy_profiles

    Purpose: Stores network connection routing strings. Used to route downloads through external proxy servers to bypass geographical restrictions or network rate-limiting.

    Field Breakdown:

        slug (TEXT PRIMARY KEY): Unique text identifier for the proxy node profile.

        title (TEXT): User-friendly descriptive label (e.g., "EU High-Speed SOCKS5 Proxy").

        proxy_string (TEXT): The full network routing connection address (e.g., "socks5://127.0.0.1:1080").

        created_at / updated_at (TEXT): Standard registration timestamps.

Table 3: site_configs

    Purpose: A mapping table that links specific websites or domains to a preferred cookie profile and proxy profile. It automates environment variables during asset discovery.

    Field Breakdown:

        slug (TEXT PRIMARY KEY): Unique identifier key.

        title (TEXT): User-friendly configuration label.

        domain (TEXT): The matching target internet domain address string.

        cookie_profile_slug (TEXT FOREIGN KEY): Links to cookie_profiles(slug). Sets to NULL if the cookie profile is deleted.

        proxy_profile_slug (TEXT FOREIGN KEY): Links to proxy_profiles(slug). Sets to NULL if the proxy profile is deleted.

        is_default (INTEGER): A strict boolean constraint (0 or 1). Determines if these routing variables should apply as a global fallback for unmapped sites.

Table 4: parsed_files

    Purpose: Stores structural metadata extracted directly from links during the asset discovery phase. This prevents redundant web requests by caching video titles and playlist dimensions.

    Field Breakdown:

        slug (TEXT PRIMARY KEY): Unique ID tracking key.

        url (TEXT): The raw, unmutated destination web address pasted by the user.

        title / sanitized_title (TEXT): The raw asset title along with an operating-system-safe title string modified for local file creation.

        is_playlist (INTEGER): Strict boolean constraint (0 or 1). Differentiates collections from standalone elements.

        parent_playlist_slug (TEXT FOREIGN KEY): Self-referential link pointing back to parsed_files(slug). Used to track individual video tracks belonging to a parent playlist array.

        playlist_name / sanitized_playlist_name (TEXT): Optional collection descriptors for organizational folder generation.

        json_metadata (TEXT): The raw, full JSON string block returned by the extractor tool for deep structural reference.

Table 5: download_jobs

    Purpose: The core tracking table for the application queue. Every item appearing in the user's active download grid represents a transactional row in this table.

    Field Breakdown:

        slug (TEXT PRIMARY KEY): Unique queue tracking key identifier.

        parsed_file_slug (TEXT FOREIGN KEY): Links directly to parsed_files(slug) to inherit title data.

        file_type (TEXT): A structural type check matching 'video', 'audio', 'subtitle', or 'direct_document'.

        associated_media_job_slug (TEXT FOREIGN KEY): Self-referential link pointing to a sister row inside download_jobs(slug). Used when a subtitle download task is bound to a matching parent video task.

        is_direct_url / direct_url (INTEGER / TEXT): Fields tracking straight media links that bypass extraction engines.

        is_from_playlist / current_part / total_parts (INTEGER): Fields used to manage batch queues sequentially.

        base_download_path / custom_download_path (TEXT): Hard disk destination paths.

        cookie_profile_slug / proxy_profile_slug (TEXT FOREIGN KEYS): Active profile hooks used for execution.

        status (TEXT): Strict status string restricted to 'pending', 'downloading', 'paused', 'completed', or 'error'.

        progress (REAL): High-speed floating-point percentage value tracking active task execution (0.00 to 100.00).

        tracking_message (TEXT): Dynamic string buffer capturing speed metrics (e.g., "4.2MiB/s ETA 00:12").

        format_string / audio_format / video_format (TEXT): The precise extraction format arguments.

        selected_subtitles (TEXT): Explicit language tags selected by the user.

        last_pid (INTEGER): Tracks the current active Operating System process ID for runtime management.

        priority_index (INTEGER): Numeric tracking value used to sort execution orders. Higher priority runs first.

Table 6: parse_logs

    Purpose: An operational diagnostics table that tracks metadata extraction history, command execution durations, and return sizes.

    Field Breakdown:

        slug (TEXT PRIMARY KEY): Log entry unique identifier key.

        parsed_file_slug (TEXT FOREIGN KEY): Links to parsed_files(slug).

        status (TEXT): Operational status flag ('running', 'success', 'failed').

        started_at / finished_at / duration_ms (TEXT / INTEGER): Diagnostic timing parameters.

        command_executed (TEXT): The exact shell string sent to the native platform command line.

        exit_code / bytes_returned (INTEGER): Process exit metrics.

Table 7: error_logs

    Purpose: Captures detailed terminal error outputs and standard error (stderr) traces when a download task fails.

    Field Breakdown:

        slug (TEXT PRIMARY KEY): Unique log tracking key.

        download_job_slug (TEXT FOREIGN KEY): Links to download_jobs(slug). If the job row is cleared, these logs are automatically deleted.

        command_executed (TEXT): The exact execution shell command string that failed.

        error_message (TEXT): The full terminal stderr dump string explaining the crash.

        is_resolved (INTEGER): A tracking boolean (0 or 1) indicating if the error was handled.

        timestamp (TEXT): Standard tracking time.

3. Communication Routes and Functional Purposes

Tauri v2 acts as an asynchronous bridge between the web frontend and the native database/OS layer. The frontend communicates through isolated IPC channels.
Route 1: process_clipboard_paste

    Purpose: Sanitizes incoming link strings.

    Logic: When the frontend detects a paste command or a clipboard action, it routes the text to this endpoint. The backend strips analytical parameters, validates the URL format, and returns a clean URL to the UI.

Route 2: discover_asset_metadata

    Purpose: Generates asset representations without writing files to disk.

    Logic: The frontend passes the sanitized URL to this command. The backend queries site_configs to apply relevant proxies or cookies, spawns a background process to fetch information, passes the raw text to our property prober, and yields a single video object or a populated playlist collection directly to the UI state store.

Route 3: trigger_job_start

    Purpose: Runs a queue download task.

    Logic: The frontend passes a unique job slug to this endpoint. The backend sets the database row state to downloading to protect data consistency, claims an slot on a thread semaphore pool (max 3 active tasks), and launches the download engine.

Route 4: request_job_pause

    Purpose: Stops a running download task.

    Logic: The frontend dispatches a job slug to this endpoint. The backend accesses the active process map, kills the matching OS process ID, releases the thread pool slot, and updates the database record status to paused.

Route 5: download-progress-token (Tauri Event Emission Pipe)

    Purpose: Pipes high-frequency performance metrics directly to the UI.

    Logic: To prevent the database from locking under rapid write operations, the download worker pushes real-time speed, size, and ETA metrics to an in-memory cache. Every second, this cache updates the database in a single batch, while streaming progress ticks to the frontend via a global event emitter. The frontend store listens to this channel to update the UI smoothly without lag.
